            "description": "Since the first invitations in 2015 more than sixty chaplains from various health care fields and from government institutions (military & prison system) have committed themselves to the Dutch Case Studies Project in Chaplaincy Care. The chaplains work in learning communities of 8 to 12 chaplains under supervision of an academic researcher. From the chaplains we ask a four year commitment in which period each will present two examples of good practice according to a set format. We are looking for feedback from clients (or significant others) and other professionals. We are interested in relations between practice and theory, in interventions and their effects, as well as in desired and reported outcomes. Research leaders are Sjaak K\u00f6rver of Tilburg School of Theology and myself. Interested persons can ask for more information on the nature of the project as well as on time and financial investment at mwalton@pthu.nl. Although the chaplains are \\participating as researchers on behalf of the profession, the research method which stays close to daily chaplaincy practice proves to be a rich and valuable learning process for one's own practice.",
